Documentation for team11.jar

The usage and implementation of the packages and classes found within the team11.jar file allows developers to create custom artificial intelligent (AI) agents to play the Angry Birds, developed by Rovio, game through an extension in Google's Chrome web browser.

See: Description

Packages 
Package Description

team11.core
This package provides the core set of tools for developing implementations of AI agents to play the Angry Birds game and also the main entry point for the jar file.
team11.core.agent
This package provides the abstract Angry Birds AI agent, Team11Agent, which an implementation of this jar file agent must extends.
team11.core.birds
This package provides the set of Birds that the Angry Birds AI agent will encounter while attempting to play the game.
team11.core.other
This package provides a few other structures including; an environment access file, and the Shot object used when shooting birds from the sling-shot.
team11.core.schema
This package provides the set of schemas used when interfacing with the game itself.
team11.core.utils
This package provides the utilities for connections, actions, and processing an implementation may require.
team11.gui
Provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) to observe the agents progress in, almost, real-time.

The usage and implementation of the packages and classes found within the team11.jar file allows developers to create custom artificial intelligent (AI) agents to play the Angry Birds, developed by Rovio, game through an extension in Google's Chrome web browser. Both Chrome and the Angry Birds game are free to download. The extension for Chrome is also free and is provided by AIBirds.org as part of their "Getting Started" kit to create AI agents to play the game.

Usage and Implementations (team11.jar)

The main entry point for implementations of an AI agent to play the Angry Birds game through the extension is the class MainEntry. The specified agent to load must extend the Team11Agent abstract class; otherwise, this will immediately terminate with the corresponding error code. Refer to the documentation for the Team11Agent on the specific requirements for implementing the agent.

Compiling

In order to compile an implementation with this jar file, use the follow: 

%> javac -classpath team11.jar [theAgent.java]

Executing

To execute an implementation of this jar file, use the following: 

%> java -jar team11.jar -d -a [theAgent.class] -l log.txt -s

As a side note; the jar file is an executable jar, thus not requiring the java -jar command. However, if running it in this manner the debug output and error output will not be displayed in the terminal and instead recorded in the systems logs. 

%> team11.jar -a [theAgent.class] -l log.txt -s

Command-Line Parameters

This application requires command-line parameters to load and initialize the various components to run an implementation of the AI agent. The list for available command-line options and parameters follows:

Option(s)Function(s)
-a --agent [path] Required to specify your implementation of the agent which must extend the Team11Agent.
-d --debug [optional] Sets the debugging for the agent to print out all debugging information when calling the internal team11.core.agent.Team11Agent#debug(String) Team11Agent#debug(String) method. Default the debugging is set to false; not to print.
-h --help [optional] If present, all other parameters are ignored and the usage for the jar file is printed to standard output, System.out.
-l --log [path] [optional] Sets the log file to be appended to when calling the internal team11.core.agent.Team11Agent#log(String) Team11Agent#log(String) method. Default prints to System.out.
-s --show [optional] Shows the debugging screen capture frame.
